The code implementing our approach is dis- tributed as part of the ConvoKit library (Chang et al., 2020), at http://convokit.cornell.edu .

Our measure is designed to be broadly applicable, re- quiring no domain-speciﬁc annotations; we provide exploratory output on justice utterances from the Supreme Court’s oral arguments in the appendix and release code implementing our approach at http://convokit.cornell.edu to encourage ex- periments in other domains.

We used tran- scripts of 668 cases, taken from the Oyez project (https://www.oyez.org/ ), averaging 120 justice utterances per case.11 Oral arguments contain more linguistic and topi- cal heterogeneiety than counseling conversations, since they cover a wide variety of cases, and be- cause the language used by each justice is more dif- ferentiated.
